{{Taxobox | name = Phycisphaerae | image = | image_caption = | phylum = [[Planctomycetes]] | classis = '''Phycisphaerae''' | domain = [[Bacteria]] | subdivision_ranks = Orders | subdivision = *[[Phycisphaerales]] <small>Fukunaga et al. 2010</small> *[[Tepidisphaerales]] <small>Kovaleva et al. 2015</small> | color = lightgrey | classis_authority = Fukunaga et al. 2010 }}
'''Phycisphaerae''' is a [[Class (biology)|class]] of aquatic [[bacteria]] Containing a single order [[Phycisphaerales]]. They reproduce by [[budding]] and are found in samples of [[algae]] in [[Marine (ocean)|marine]] [[water]].<ref name="ncbi">NITE Biological Resource Center (NBRC), National Institute of Technology and Evaluation (NITE), Chiba, Japan, [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19700920|Phycisphaera mikurensis gen. nov., sp. nov., isolated from a marine alga, and proposal of Phycisphaeraceae fam. nov., Phycisphaerales ord. nov. and Phycisphaerae classis nov. in the phylum Planctomycetes], August 2009. retrieved 5 December 2015.</ref> Organisms in this group are spherical<ref name="ncbi" /> and have a [[holdfast]], at the tip of a thin cylindrical extension from the cell body called the stalk, at the nonreproductive end that helps them to attach to each other during budding.
